Inspecting C:N effects on CUE and steady states

Summary

What is the effect of changing C:N of litter input on carbon use efficiency CUE and on predicted steady states?

Here, we vary the C:N ratio of inputs and plot the resulting steady state of stocks and other variables.

Model versions

  • SESAM4a: soil enzyme steady allocation model with microbial turnover rate by predation increases linearly with microbial biomass.

Setup parameters and drivers

Mass units are \(gC/m^2\), \(gN/m^2\) or \(gP/m^2\). Time unit is \(yr\).

require(sesam)

parms0 <- list(
  cnB = 8.3       ##<< Cleveland07, grassland
  , cnBW = 8.4    ##<< C/N ratio of cell material that go to RC  (cell walls) NRSOM Tipping 16
  , cnE = 3.2     # Sterner02: Protein (Fig. 2.2.), high N investment (low P)
  , cnIR = 4.5     ##<< between micr and enzyme signal
  , cnIL = 30      ##<< N litter OM
  , kmN = 0.3*0.01*365  ##<< /yr enzyme turnover 1% turning over each day
  , kNB = 0.8      ##<< amount of recycling enzyme turnover by biomass (added to uptake instead of RC )
  , kR = 1/(50)    ##<< 1/(x years)
  , kL = 1/(1)     ##<< 1/(x years)
  , aE = 0.001*365 ##<< C biomass allocated to enzymes gC/day /microbial biomass
  #, km = 0.3       ##<< enzyme half-saturation constant
  , m = 0.02*365   ##<< maintenance respiration rate   gC/day /microbial biomass
  , tau = 1/60*365 ##<< biomass turnover rate (12 days)
  , eps = 0.5      ##<< carbon use efficiency
  , epsPred = 0.3  ##<< carbon use efficiency of microbial tvr (predators respire)
  , iR = 0         ##<< input modelled explicitely
  , iL = 300       ##<< g/m2 input per year (half NPP)
  , plantNUp = 0   ##<< plant N uptake balancing N inputs
  , useFixedAlloc = FALSE    ##<< set to true to use fixed enzyme allocation (alpha = 0.5)
  , kIPlant = 10.57 #0.0289652*365         ##<< plant uptake iP I
  , iB = 0.38 * 10.57 #0.0110068*365   ##<< immobilization flux iB I
  , iI = 0         ##<< input of mineral N
  , l = 0.96 #0.00262647*365       ##<< leaching rate of mineralN l I
  , nu = 0.9       ##<< microbial N use efficiency
  , isEnzymeMassFlux = TRUE  ##<< steady state BC solution accounts for enyzme mass fluxes
  , nuP = 0.3      ##<< microbial uptake of depolymerized P, (1-nuP) is mineralized
  , cpE = 100     ##<< Sterner02, protein with no P
  , cpB = 47.3    ##<< Cleveland07, grassland
  , cpBW = 61     ##<< NRSOM Tipping16
  , cpIR = 61
  , cpIL = 919    ##<< NPSOM Tipping 16
  , iBP = 0.38 * 10.57 # start with same as N
  , cW = 0.8 # proportion of cell wall within microbial biomass
  , B0 = 0  # minimal biomass, below which predation rate is zero
  , tauP = 0.1 # slope of predation rate with biomass
  , nuP = 0.01 # DOP almost all mineralized before taken up
)
parms0 <- within(parms0,{
  lP <- l       # leaching rate of inorganic P equals that of N
  kiPlant <- 0  # no plant uptake
  kIPPlant <- kIPlant  # plant uptake rate of P equals that of N
  iIP <- l      # assume no P inputs compensate for leaching
})
# assure no P-limitation
parms0 <- within(parms0,{
  plantNUpAbs <- iL/cnIL
  lP <- kIPlant <- 0    # no leaching of P
  iBP <- 1e6            # no limit of P immobilization flux
})
# neglect influence of inorganic pools (keep them at fixed initial values)
parms0$isFixedI <- TRUE

For simplicity model drivers are currently prescibed as constant parameters.

drivers <- list(
  iR = 0           ##<< input of residue litter
  , iL = 400       ##<< input of labile litter
  , cnIR = 7       ##<< C/N ratio of the residue litter input
  , cnIL = 30      ##<< C/N ratio of labile litter input
  , cpIR = 40      ##<< C/P ratio of the residue litter input
  , cpIL = 919     ##<< C/P ratio of the labile litter input, NPSOM Tipping16
  , iI = 0         ##<< input of mineral N
  , iIP = 0        ##<< input of labile mineral P
)
parms0 <- c(parms0[setdiff(names(parms0),names(drivers))], drivers)

The initial pools must be specified.

x0 <- c( #aE = 0.001*365
  BC = 17                    ##<< microbial biomass in C units
  , RC = 1100                ##<< C residue OM
  , RN = 1100/parms0$cnIR   ##<< N residue OM 
  , RP = 1100/parms0$cpIR   ##<< P residue OM 
  , LC = 100                 ##<< C litter OM
  , LN = 100/parms0$cnIL    ##<< N litter OM 
  , LP = 100/parms0$cpIL    ##<< P litter OM 
  , I =  0.1               ##<< inorganic N pool 
  , IP =  0.01              ##<< inorganic P pool 
  , alpha = 0.5             ##<< microbial community partitioning [0,1]
)

Run to steady state

The first simulation runs to steady state for given parameters.

  times <- c(seq(0,500, length.out = 101), 2000)
  res <- res1 <- as.data.frame(lsoda( x0, times, derivSesam4a, parms = parms0))
  xE <-  unlist(tail(res,1)) # final state
  x0S <- xE[1 + seq_along(x0)]

Plot approaching the steady state.

CN scenarios

Starting from this steady state, several scenarios of changing C:N ratio of litter inputs are simulated. This means for same C input, varying the N inputs.

While the original run was C-limited, perform a run that is N-limited by increasing the C:N ratio of litter input.

parms <- within(parms0, cnIL <- 80)
times <- c(seq(0,500, length.out = 101), 2000)
res <- as.data.frame(lsoda( x0S, times, derivSesam4a, parms = parms))
xE <- unlist(tail(res,1)) # final state

Next, inspect the steady state obtained after a range of C:N litter inputs.

cnILs <- seq(parms0$cnIL, 70, length.out = 21)
times <- c(0, 2000)
xEs <- map_dfr(cnILs, function(cnILi){
  parms <- within(parms0, cnIL <- cnILi)
  res <- as.data.frame(lsoda( x0S, times, derivSesam4a, parms = parms))
  xE <- unlist(tail(res,1)) # final state
  cbind(as.data.frame(t(xE)), cnIL = cnILi)
})
#xEs

Plotting steady state against C:N of litter input.

In steady state, microbes are C -limited up to litter C:N ratios of about 55. This seems counter-intuitive, but is actually reasonable.

In steady state, all the organic N inputs to the soil will be mineralized, i.e. \(\Phi_{Total} = \beta_{iL} i_L\). Immobilization only occurs if the other N mineralization fluxes (during uptake and during turnover) exceed the N litter inputs.

Up to this point where N actually limits microbial growth, stocks do not change. Afterwards they decrease together with microbial biomass stocks and CUE.

Note, also that apparent CUE is lower than the intrinsic catabolic CUE, \(\epsilon = 0.5\), due to investments into enzymes and maintenance that decrease the C available for biomass synthesis. Basing CUE on adding microbial biomass synthesis and measured respiration (including respiration by predation), \(cue_{Syn}\), yields similar estimates as those based on modeled microbial uptake, \(cue_{Def}\).

DOM and synthesis flux composition

Despite the high C/N ratios of litter, the substrate for microbial synthesis has more nutrients, due to decomposition of N-rich residue, and turnover of microbial biomass and enzymes.

cnDOM is the C:N ratio of the disolved organic matter (DOM), and cnSyn is the C:N ratio of the matter flux used for biosynthesis and mineralization. The latter includes immobilization of nutrients and usage of starved biomass (cryptic) growth.

Unitl a threshold elemental ratio, TER, of about 22, there is mineralization of microbial N uptake from DOM. At DOM C/N ratios of slightly above this value, immobilization of inorganic N kepps the synthesis flux at the co-limitation.

Decomposition of residue OM, \(dec_{NR}\) is the largest contribution to synthesis N flux. Direct flux of microbial turnover to DOM, \(dec_{NB}\) also contributes substantially, and in the used parameterization also the flux by enzyme production and turnover, \(dec_{NE}\). At steady state there is no microbial starvation, \(starv_N\), and immobilization of inorganic N, \(immo_N\), contributes a small share when organic N is limiting.
